answers.body_markdown:
One option is to use a regular expression: match characters until lookahead matches `/`, followed by non-`/` characters, followed by the end of the string:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const str = &#39;Computers/Hard-drive/5GB/Brand&#39;;
    const result = str.match(/.*(?=\/[^/]+$)/)[0];
    console.log(result);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You could split, slice untile the item before the last one and join the array to a string.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var string = &#39;Computers/Hard-drive/5GB/Brand&#39;,
        result = string.split(&#39;/&#39;).slice(0, -1).join(&#39;/&#39;);

    console.log(result);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You have lots of options.

1. The regular expression approach
2. The `lastIndexOf` approach
3. The `split`/`join` approach

Personally I prefer the simplicity and lack of unnecessary intermediate objects that #2 provides.

## 1\. The regular expression approach

...either [as shown by CertainPerformance](https://stackoverflow.com/a/58362721/157247) or a version using `replace` to replace all characters after the last `/`.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let str = &quot;Computers/Hard-drive/5GB/Brand&quot;;
    str = str.replace(/\/[^\/]+$/, &quot;&quot;);
    console.log(str);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

This works just fine if there isn&#39;t any slash; it just returns the string unchanged.

## 2\. The `lastIndexOf` version

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let str = &quot;Computers/Hard-drive/5GB/Brand&quot;;
    const index = str.lastIndexOf(&quot;/&quot;);
    str = str.substring(0, index);
    console.log(str);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Note that the above assumes there will be a slash. To not make that assumption, you need to add a guard in case `index` is `-1`:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let str = &quot;Computers/Hard-drive/5GB/Brand&quot;;
    let index = str.lastIndexOf(&quot;/&quot;);
    if (index !== -1) {
        str = str.substring(0, index);
    }
    console.log(str);

    str = &quot;Computers&quot;;
    index = str.lastIndexOf(&quot;/&quot;);
    if (index !== -1) {
        str = str.substring(0, index);
    }
    console.log(str);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

## 3\. The `split` and `join` approach

...[as shown by Nina](https://stackoverflow.com/a/58362735/157247). *(Removed mine when I saw hers, which is much more concise without being harder to read.)* Note that Nina&#39;s implementation also assumes there will be a slash, you&#39;ll need to do a check on the result of `split` (e.g., is it more than one long) to handle the case where there isn&#39;t one.

You can try with [**`String.prototype.lastIndexOf()`**][1] and [**`String.prototype.substring()`**][2]

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var directory = &#39;Computers/Hard-drive/5GB/Brand&#39;
    var pos = directory.lastIndexOf(&quot;/&quot;);
    var result = directory.substring(0, pos);
    console.log(result);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/lastIndexOf
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/substring

